images={}
images_histo={}
# compute image histograms
for path in glob.glob(os.path.join('images',"*.png")):
    img = cv2.imread(path)
    img = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)

    # extract a 3D RGB color histogram from the image, using 8 bins per
    # channel, normalize, and update the index
    # https://docs.opencv.org/4.0.1/d6/dc7/group__imgproc__hist.html#ga4b2b5fd75503ff9e6844cc4dcdaed35d
    hist = cv2.calcHist(
        [img],                   # images
        [0, 1, 2],               # channels
        None,                    # mask
        [8, 8, 8],               # histSize
        [0, 256, 0, 256, 0, 256] # ranges
    )
    # https://docs.opencv.org/4.0.1/d2/de8/group__core__array.html#ga87eef7ee3970f86906d69a92cbf064bd
    hist = cv2.normalize(hist, None)
    hist = hist.flatten()               # make 1 dim array (8*8*8=512) fro
    
    m histSize [8,8,8] array 
    name = os.path.basename(path)
    images[name] = img
    images_histo[name]=hist # store with image name as key

1. Using opencv¶

In [53]:
def using_opencv(methodName, method):
    results = {}
    reverse = False
    if methodName in ("Correlation", "Intersection"):
        reverse = True
    
    for imgname, histo in images_histo.items():
        # compute distance between doge.png and all other images
        dist = cv2.compareHist(images_histo["doge.png"], histo, method)
        results[imgname] = dist
        #print "###", imgname, dist
    
    # sort the results
    results = sorted([(v, k) for (k, v) in results.items()], reverse = reverse)
    #print results

    # initialize the results figure
    fig = plt.figure("Results: %s" % (methodName), figsize=(10,3))
    fig.suptitle(methodName)
    
    # loop over the results
    for (i, (v, k)) in enumerate(results):
        # show the result
        ax = fig.add_subplot(1, len(images), i + 1)
        ax.set_title("%s: %.2f" % (k, v))
        plt.imshow(images[k])
        plt.axis("off")

from scipy.spatial import distance as dist

def using_scipy(methodName, method):
    results = {}
    for imgname, histo in images_histo.items():
        d = method(images_histo["doge.png"], histo)
        results[imgname] = d
    results = sorted([(v, k) for (k, v) in results.items()])
    fig = plt.figure("Results: %s" % (methodName), figsize=(10,3))
    fig.suptitle(methodName)
    for (i, (v, k)) in enumerate(results):
        # show the result
        ax = fig.add_subplot(1, len(images), i + 1)
        ax.set_title("%s: %.2f" % (k, v))
        plt.imshow(images[k])
        plt.axis("off")

Roll your own¶

In [82]:
import numpy as np

def chi2_distance(histA, histB, eps = 1e-10):
    # compute the chi-squared distance
    d = 0.5 * np.sum([((a - b) ** 2) / (a + b + eps)
        for (a, b) in zip(histA, histB)])

    # return the chi-squared distance
    return d

def using_rollyourown():
    results = {}
    for imgname, histo in images_histo.items():
        d = chi2_distance(images_histo["doge.png"], histo)
        results[imgname] = d
        
    results = sorted([(v, k) for (k, v) in results.items()])
    fig = plt.figure("Results: Roll your own", figsize=(10,3))
    fig.suptitle("Roll your own")
